//handles all info outputting commands
alias info "i1; i2; i3; i4; i5; i6; i7; i8; i9; i10; i11;"

alias i1 "echo <h2>What is this?</h2>"
alias i2 "echo <p>This is a personal project and a nightmare. I had so much fun with it!</p>"
alias i3 "echo <p>This is a web server entirely hosted and served from a vanilla CSGO Legacy client developer console. There is no Apache, Python, VScript, or any other bypasses.</p>"
alias i4 "echo <p>Source engine games after LFD2 have a launch option to expose their developer consoles on to any port. This port is designed to be telnetted into and act 1 to 1 as the dev console.</p>"
alias i5 "echo <p>This port can be connected to by the web browser, though. By default, this does nothing, as the Source Engine dev console obviously does not speak http.</p>"
alias i6 "echo <p>When a browser connects, each individual header of the browser GET request is interpreted as a command by the console.</p>"
alias i7 "echo <p>Using the Source Engine alias command, I am able to duck tape a proper http header and HTML page to the GET command. This command is the first thing sent by every browser in a get request.</p>"
alias i8 "echo <p>Finally, I can use javascript I wrote on the HTML page to fetch the CSGO client. Each button on this site sends a fetch request with an arbitrary illegitimate http request type.</p>"
alias i9 "echo <p>I can then make an alias for these http request types in Source whenever they are sent. I do this the same way I did for get requests. These aliases map to in game inputs.</p>"
alias i10 "echo <p>This effectively creates a controller for CSGO that communicates remotely over TCP through the browser. I plan to livestream my client and then allow viewers to control the game from this site.</p>"
alias i11 "echo <p>This was not without struggle. The Source Engine does not like to echo special characters like semicolons and quotations. Programming this felt like I was trying to make SQL injection bypass a filter.</p>"

